Here is a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
  // open the file
  std::ifstream file("file.txt");

  // create a string to store the word we are looking for
  std::string word("word");

  // count the occurrences of the word in the file
  int count = 0;
  while (file >> line) {
    // check if the line contains the word we are looking for
    if (line.find(word) != std::string::npos) {
      count++;
    }
  }
  // close the file
  file.close();

  // print the result
  std::cout << "The word '";
  std::cout << word << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file.";
  std::cout << std::endl;

  return 0;
}
```

This program reads the content of a text file line by line, using an ifstream object. Inside the loop, the file is read line by line and the word is found using the find() method. The occurrences of the word are counted and stored in a variable. Finally, the result is printed to the console. You can modify the file name and the word to run the program with your specific input.

